'''Emmeline Lewis Lloyd''' (18 November, 1827 <U+2013> 22 September, 1913) was an early [[British]] alpine mountaineer.

==Life==
[[File:Nantgwyllt manor house.gif|thumb|left|Nantgwyllt manor house home of the Lewis Lloyds inc. Emmelinenow flooded. in Powys]]
Lloyd was born in [[Nantgwyllt]] in 1827. She was the fourth child. Her father and mother owned the manor house in the, [[Elan Valley Reservoirs|now flooded, Elan valley]].<ref name=wbo/> Her father, Thomas Lewis-Lloyd, was a Justice of the Peace and [[High Sheriff of Cardiganshire]] in 1822.<ref>Nicholas, Annals and Antiquities of the Counties and County Families of Wales, Vol. 2 p. 924</ref> Lloyd was an independent child and she ran a farm at farmed at [[Llandyfaelog Fach]] that bred mountain ponies. Her hobbies included walking, fishing and otter hunting. She  would tell stories of her exploits climbing the alps with her sister Bessie or [[Isabella Charlet-Straton|Isabella Straton]]. One of her guides had been Jean Charlet, a French [[mountain guide]] from [[Chamonix]], who had been a groom in Nantgwyllt for a year.<ref name=wbo/>

Lewis Lloyd and Stratton had been two of the very rare women who climbed the [[Alps]] and [[Pyrenees]] in the 1860s and 70s. In 1869 just four years after it was first climbed<ref name=wbo/> they made an unsuccessful attempt on the [[Matterhorn]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wbo.llgc.org.uk/en/s3-LEWI-EMM-1827.html|publisher=Welsh Biography Online|title= Lewis Lloyd, Emmeline |last=Rhys|first=Ioan Bowen|accessdate=3 April 2014}}</ref> In 1870 they became the first women to climb [[Monte Viso]]<ref name=dnb/> and the following year they made the first ascent of Aiguille du Moine guided by Joseph Simond.<ref name=wbo/> Lewis Lloyd retired from climbing in 1873, but Straton continued to climb with [[Jean Charlet]]<ref name=dnb>{{cite book|title=[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]|chapter=Straton, (Mary) Isabella Charlet- (1838<U+2013>1918)|last=Hansen|first=Peter H.|year=2004|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]}}</ref> and she eventually married him.

Lloyd died at Hampstead Hill Gardens in [[London]]. She is buried at [[Cwmdauddwr|Llansanffraid Cwmteuddwr]] and the church there has a memorial.<ref name=wbo>[http://wbo.llgc.org.uk/en/s3-LEWI-EMM-1827.html LEWIS LLOYD , EMMELINE], Welsh Biography online, retrieved 5 April 2014</ref>

